335. The way in which sensation begins with the quarta natura of the soul, and is transmitted step by step to the body, was described 11. 246—251: it is by the combined atomio motions of soul and body that sensation is ‘kindled and blown into flame throughout our flesh.’ See Introd. p. xiii.

Lucr. here speaks as if sensation were produced by the mere juxta- position of body and soul, just as water is produced by the juxtaposition of oxygen and hydrogen. But this is not so: sensation is inherent in the soul, and is communicated by the soul to the body (cf. 1. 3 57).
